<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
JAZZ BASSIST LOUIS VOLA DIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jazz bassist Louis Vola, a founding member of the legendary Hot Club Quintet in 
the 1930s, has died after a long illness, friends reported today. 
</P>
<P>
He was 88. Born in the Riviera town of La-Seyne-Sur-Mer, Vola helped found the 
quintet in 1934 and played bass on the first recordings by fellow group members 
Django Reinhardt and Stephane Grappelli. 
</P>
<P>
Vola went on to play bass in Ray Ventura's orchestra. He also backed up Benny 
Carter and Duke Ellington and the French singers Charles Trenet, Yves Montand 
and Georges Brassens. 
</P>
<P>
Friends said Vola died last week in a Paris hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
